{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6605c5ed-d39e-4a81-ab4a-984247c775bf","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **Via Finder:** Open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports**\n2. **Via Terminal:**\n   ```\n   ls ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips\n   ```\n   Older macOS versions may use `.crash` instead of `.ips`.\n\n3. Look for a file named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**To get a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n# Then reproduce the crash — core file goes to /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\n> 💡 Once you have the `.ips` file, I can help symbolicate the .NET runtime frames using the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill. Just share the file!","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a4788008-cc0a-4088-939b-e34a65b613af","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostics question — let me check if any of my skills are relevant.\n\nThe `dump-collect` skill is about configuring and collecting crash dumps for modern .NET applications. This seems relevant. Let me also check `apple-crash-symbolication` — that's about symbolicating Apple crash logs, which is related but not exactly what they're asking (they want to find the crash report first, not symbolicate it).\n\nThe `dump-collect` skill says: \"USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps for CoreCLR or NativeAOT, capturing dumps from running .NET processes, setting up dump collection in Docker or Kubernetes, using dotnet-dump collect or createdump.\"\n\n\nThe `dump-collect` skill looks like the right fit for this situation, so I'll use it.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"4187:271EF2:62EB9E2:6C277CF:69F1632C"},"id":"25e49572-866b-4c9e-8a3a-ccb860e1d8e4","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:47:36.878Z","parentId":"719a4f9